---

1. Loan-Like ETH Liquidity Interaction

Goal

User A temporarily needs ETH liquidity from User B.

This is not a permanent swap.

It is:

temporary ETH lending,

socially tracked,

reputation-producing.



---

Step-by-Step Flow

Step 1 — Borrow Request Signal

User A requests ETH liquidity from User B.

To initiate trust interaction:

User A:

mints 1 wei SOS to User B through the logger contract.


Logger records:

User A requested liquidity,

User B became liquidity provider candidate,

interaction timestamp.


This acts as:

trust initiation,

intent signal,

interaction anchor.



---

Step 2 — ETH Transfer

User B sends ETH liquidity to User A.

Example:

gas funds,

temporary liquidity,

activity funding,

emergency ETH.


ETH transfer itself may happen:

directly wallet-to-wallet,

or through lender router contract.



---

Step 3 — Repayment

Later:

User A repays ETH to User B.


Repayment completes trust cycle.


---

Step 4 — Repayment Trust Mint

After repayment:

User B:

mints 1 wei SOS to User A through logger contract.


Logger records:

User A successfully repaid,

User B confirmed repayment,

successful trust completion.



---

Reputation Effects

User	Reputation Signal

User A	trustworthy borrower
User B	trustworthy liquidity provider


Both gain:

positive network reputation,

stronger trust history,

future interaction credibility.



---

Important Economic Property

ETH is:

recycled,

not permanently consumed.


SOS is:

accumulated as interaction history.


So:

\text{ETH} = \text{circulating liquidity}

while:

\text{SOS} = \text{persistent trust memory}


