2. Mint-as-a-Service Reputation Interaction

This becomes the onboarding and mint-authority layer.


---

Goal

User A wants:

N SOS minted,

but prefers trusted mint provider User B.


Reason:

User B has strong reputation,

trusted history,

reliable mint behavior.



---

Step-by-Step Flow

Step 1 — Mint Request Signal

User A:

mints 1 wei SOS to User B.


This signals:

trust request,

mint-service request,

acknowledgment of User B reputation.


Logger records:

User A selected User B as mint provider.



---

Step 2 — Payment for Service

User A sends ETH to User B covering:

gas cost for minting N SOS,

optional tip,

service compensation.


This creates:

real economic cost,

anti-spam pressure,

service marketplace dynamics.



---

Step 3 — Mint Execution

User B mints:

N SOS to User A.


This acts as:

onboarding,

reputation delegation,

trust extension.



---

Step 4 — Reputation Recording

Logger records:

User B successfully provided mint service,

User A successfully compensated provider.



---

Reputation Effects

User	Reputation Signal

User A	cooperative participant
User B	trusted mint operator


Both gain:

stronger network trust,

higher interaction credibility,

expanded social-economic graph.



